nodeType.name: nodeType
nodeType.comment:
The type of node.

This value is one of:

  • dart-dom-html.Node.ATTRIBUTE_NODE if this node is an attribute.
  • [CDATA_SECTION_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.CDataSection.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.COMMENT_NODE if this node is a dart-dom-html.Comment.
  • [DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.DocumentFragment.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.DOCUMENT_NODE if this node is a dart-dom-html.Document.
  • [DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE] if this node is a DocumentType node.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.ELEMENT_NODE if this node is an dart-dom-html.Element.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.ENTITY_NODE if this node is an entity.
  • [ENTITY_REFERENCE_NODE] if this node is an entity reference.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.NOTATION_NODE if this node is a notation.
  • [PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE] if this node is a dart-dom-html.ProcessingInstruction.
  • dart-dom-html.Node.TEXT_NODE if this node is a dart-dom-html.Text node.

Other resources

  • Node.nodeType from MDN.

innerHtml=.name: innerHtml=
innerHtml=.comment:
Parses the HTML fragment and sets it as the contents of this element.

This uses the default sanitization behavior to sanitize the HTML fragment, use dart-dom-html.Element.setInnerHtml to override the default behavior.

attributes.name: attributes
attributes.comment:
All attributes on this element.

Any modifications to the attribute map will automatically be applied to this element.

This only includes attributes which are not in a namespace (such as 'xlink:href'), additional attributes can be accessed via dart-dom-html.Element.getNamespacedAttributes.

children.name: children
children.comment:
List of the direct children of this element.

This collection can be used to add and remove elements from the document.

var item = new DivElement();
item.text = 'Something';
document.body.children.add(item) // Item is now displayed on the page.
for (var element in document.body.children) {
  element.style.background = 'red'; // Turns every child of body red.
}

classes.name: classes
classes.comment:
The set of CSS classes applied to this element.

This set makes it easy to add, remove or toggle the classes applied to this element.

element.classes.add('selected');
element.classes.toggle('isOnline');
element.classes.remove('selected');

dataset.name: dataset
dataset.comment:
Allows access to all custom data attributes (data-*) set on this element.

The keys for the map must follow these rules:

  • The name must not begin with 'xml'.
  • The name cannot contain a semi-colon (';').
  • The name cannot contain any capital letters.

Any keys from markup will be converted to camel-cased keys in the map.

For example, HTML specified as:

<div data-my-random-value='value'></div>

Would be accessed in Dart as:

var value = element.dataset['myRandomValue'];

See also:

  • Custom data attributes

client.name: client
client.comment: Gets the position of this element relative to the client area of the page.

offset.name: offset
offset.comment: Gets the offset of this element relative to its offsetParent.

xtag.name: xtag
xtag.comment:
Experimental support for web components. This field stores a reference to the component implementation. It was inspired by Mozilla's x-tags project. Please note: in the future it may be possible to extend Element from your class, in which case this field will be deprecated.

If xtag has not been set, it will simply return this dart-dom-html.Element.

shadowRoot.comment:

contentEdge.name: contentEdge
contentEdge.comment:
Access this element's content position.

This returns a rectangle with the dimenions actually available for content in this element, in pixels, regardless of this element's box-sizing property. Unlike dart-dom-html.Element.getBoundingClientRect, the dimensions of this rectangle will return the same numerical height if the element is hidden or not.

Important note: use of this method will perform CSS calculations that can trigger a browser reflow. Therefore, use of this property during an animation frame is discouraged. See also: Browser Reflow

paddingEdge.name: paddingEdge
paddingEdge.comment:
Access the dimensions and position of this element's content + padding box.

This returns a rectangle with the dimenions actually available for content in this element, in pixels, regardless of this element's box-sizing property. Unlike dart-dom-html.Element.getBoundingClientRect, the dimensions of this rectangle will return the same numerical height if the element is hidden or not. This can be used to retrieve jQuery's innerHeight value for an element. This is also a rectangle equalling the dimensions of clientHeight and clientWidth.

Important note: use of this method will perform CSS calculations that can trigger a browser reflow. Therefore, use of this property during an animation frame is discouraged. See also: Browser Reflow

borderEdge.name: borderEdge
borderEdge.comment:
Access the dimensions and position of this element's content + padding + border box.

This returns a rectangle with the dimenions actually available for content in this element, in pixels, regardless of this element's box-sizing property. Unlike dart-dom-html.Element.getBoundingClientRect, the dimensions of this rectangle will return the same numerical height if the element is hidden or not. This can be used to retrieve jQuery's outerHeight value for an element.

Important note: use of this method will perform CSS calculations that can trigger a browser reflow. Therefore, use of this property during an animation frame is discouraged. See also: Browser Reflow

marginEdge.name: marginEdge
marginEdge.comment:
Access the dimensions and position of this element's content + padding + border + margin box.

This returns a rectangle with the dimenions actually available for content in this element, in pixels, regardless of this element's box-sizing property. Unlike dart-dom-html.Element.getBoundingClientRect, the dimensions of this rectangle will return the same numerical height if the element is hidden or not. This can be used to retrieve jQuery's outerHeight value for an element.

Important note: use of this method will perform CSS calculations that can trigger a browser reflow. Therefore, use of this property during an animation frame is discouraged. See also: Browser Reflow

documentOffset.name: documentOffset
documentOffset.comment:
Provides the coordinates of the element relative to the top of the document.

This method is the Dart equivalent to jQuery's offset method.

html.name: html
html.comment:
Creates an HTML element from a valid fragment of HTML.

var element = new Element.html('<div class="foo">content</div>');

The HTML fragment should contain only one single root element, any leading or trailing text nodes will be removed.

The HTML fragment is parsed as if it occurred within the context of a <body> tag, this means that special elements such as <caption> which must be parsed within the scope of a <table> element will be dropped. Use dart-dom-html.Element.createFragment to parse contextual HTML fragments.

Unless a validator is provided this will perform the default validation and remove all scriptable elements and attributes.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.NodeValidator

created.name: created
created.comment:
Custom element creation constructor.

This constructor is used by the DOM when a custom element has been created. It can only be invoked by subclasses of Element from that classes created constructor.

class CustomElement extends Element {
  factory CustomElement() => new Element.tag('x-custom');

  CustomElement.created() : super.created() {
     // Perform any element initialization.
  }
}
document.register('x-custom', CustomElement);

tag.name: tag
tag.comment:
Creates the HTML element specified by the tag name.

This is similar to dart-dom-html.Document.createElement. dart-dom-html.Element.Element-tag.tag should be a valid HTML tag name. If dart-dom-html.Element.Element-tag.tag is an unknown tag then this will create an dart-dom-html.UnknownElement.

var divElement = new Element.tag('div');
print(divElement is DivElement); // 'true'
var myElement = new Element.tag('unknownTag');
print(myElement is UnknownElement); // 'true'

For standard elements it is more preferable to use the type constructors:

var element = new DivElement();

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.Element.isTagSupported

querySelectorAll.comment:
Finds all descendent elements of this element that match the specified group of selectors.

dart-dom-html.Element.querySelectorAll.selectors should be a string using CSS selector syntax.

var items = element.querySelectorAll('.itemClassName');

For details about CSS selector syntax, see the CSS selector specification.

getNamespacedAttributes.name: getNamespacedAttributes
getNamespacedAttributes.comment:
Gets a map for manipulating the attributes of a particular namespace.

This is primarily useful for SVG attributes such as xref:link.

getComputedStyle.name: getComputedStyle
getComputedStyle.comment:
The set of all CSS values applied to this element, including inherited and default values.

The computedStyle contains values that are inherited from other sources, such as parent elements or stylesheets. This differs from the dart-dom-html.Element.style property, which contains only the values specified directly on this element.

PseudoElement can be values such as ::after, ::before, ::marker, ::line-marker.

See also:

  • CSS Inheritance and Cascade
  • Pseudo-elements

appendText.name: appendText
appendText.comment: Adds the specified text after the last child of this element.

appendHtml.name: appendHtml
appendHtml.comment: Parses the specified text as HTML and adds the resulting node after the last child of this element.

isTagSupported.name: isTagSupported
isTagSupported.comment:
Checks to see if the tag name is supported by the current platform.

The tag should be a valid HTML tag name.

enteredView.name: enteredView
enteredView.comment: Called by the DOM when this element has been inserted into the live document.

leftView.name: leftView
leftView.comment: Called by the DOM when this element has been removed from the live document.

attributeChanged.name: attributeChanged
attributeChanged.comment: Called by the DOM whenever an attribute on this has been changed.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment:
The string representation of this element.

This is equivalent to reading the dart-dom-html.Element.localName property.

scrollIntoView.name: scrollIntoView
scrollIntoView.comment:
Scrolls this element into view.

Only one of of the alignment options may be specified at a time.

If no options are specified then this will attempt to scroll the minimum amount needed to bring the element into view.

Note that alignCenter is currently only supported on WebKit platforms. If alignCenter is specified but not supported then this will fall back to alignTop.

See also:

  • scrollIntoView
  • scrollIntoViewIfNeeded

insertAdjacentText.name: insertAdjacentText
insertAdjacentText.comment:
Inserts text into the DOM at the specified location.

To see the possible values for dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentText.where, read the doc for dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentHtml.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentHtml

insertAdjacentHtml.name: insertAdjacentHtml
insertAdjacentHtml.comment:
Parses text as an HTML fragment and inserts it into the DOM at the specified location.

The dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentHtml.where parameter indicates where to insert the HTML fragment:

  • 'beforeBegin': Immediately before this element.
  • 'afterBegin': As the first child of this element.
  • 'beforeEnd': As the last child of this element.

  • 'afterEnd': Immediately after this element.

    var html = '<div class="something">content</div>'; // Inserts as the first child document.body.insertAdjacentHtml('afterBegin', html); var createdElement = document.body.children0; print(createdElement.classes0); // Prints 'something'

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentText
  • dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentElement

insertAdjacentElement.name: insertAdjacentElement
insertAdjacentElement.comment:
Inserts dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentElement.element into the DOM at the specified location.

To see the possible values for dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentElement.where, read the doc for dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentHtml.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.Element.insertAdjacentHtml

matches.name: matches
matches.comment: Checks if this element matches the CSS selectors.

matchesWithAncestors.name: matchesWithAncestors
matchesWithAncestors.comment: Checks if this element or any of its parents match the CSS selectors.

createShadowRoot.name: createShadowRoot
createShadowRoot.comment:
Creates a new shadow root for this shadow host.

Other resources

  • Shadow DOM 101 from HTML5Rocks.

  • Shadow DOM specification from W3C.

offsetTo.name: offsetTo
offsetTo.comment:
Provides the offset of this element's dart-dom-html.Element.borderEdge relative to the specified dart-dom-html.Element.offsetTo.parent.

This is the Dart equivalent of jQuery's position method. Unlike jQuery's position, however, dart-dom-html.Element.offsetTo.parent can be any parent element of this, rather than only this's immediate dart-dom-html.Element.offsetParent. If the specified element is not an offset parent or transitive offset parent to this element, an dart-core.ArgumentError is thrown.

createFragment.name: createFragment
createFragment.comment:
Create a DocumentFragment from the HTML fragment and ensure that it follows the sanitization rules specified by the validator or treeSanitizer.

If the default validation behavior is too restrictive then a new NodeValidator should be created, either extending or wrapping a default validator and overriding the validation APIs.

The treeSanitizer is used to walk the generated node tree and sanitize it. A custom treeSanitizer can also be provided to perform special validation rules but since the API is more complex to implement this is discouraged.

The returned tree is guaranteed to only contain nodes and attributes which are allowed by the provided validator.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.NodeValidator
  • dart-dom-html.NodeTreeSanitizer

setInnerHtml.name: setInnerHtml
setInnerHtml.comment:
Parses the HTML fragment and sets it as the contents of this element. This ensures that the generated content follows the sanitization rules specified by the validator or treeSanitizer.

If the default validation behavior is too restrictive then a new NodeValidator should be created, either extending or wrapping a default validator and overriding the validation APIs.

The treeSanitizer is used to walk the generated node tree and sanitize it. A custom treeSanitizer can also be provided to perform special validation rules but since the API is more complex to implement this is discouraged.

The resulting tree is guaranteed to only contain nodes and attributes which are allowed by the provided validator.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.NodeValidator
  • dart-dom-html.NodeTreeSanitizer

getBoundingClientRect.name: getBoundingClientRect
getBoundingClientRect.comment:
Returns the smallest bounding rectangle that encompasses this element's padding, scrollbar, and border.

Other resources

  • Element.getBoundingClientRect from MDN.

  • The getBoundingClientRect() method from W3C.

getClientRects.name: getClientRects
getClientRects.comment:
Returns a list of bounding rectangles for each box associated with this element.

Other resources

  • Element.getClientRects from MDN.

  • The getClientRects() method from W3C.

getDestinationInsertionPoints.name: getDestinationInsertionPoints
getDestinationInsertionPoints.comment:
Returns a list of shadow DOM insertion points to which this element is distributed.

Other resources

  • Shadow DOM specification from W3C.

getElementsByClassName.name: getElementsByClassName
getElementsByClassName.comment:
Returns a list of nodes with the given class name inside this element.

Other resources

  • getElementsByClassName from MDN.

  • DOM specification from W3C.

querySelector.name: querySelector
querySelector.comment:
Finds the first descendant element of this element that matches the specified group of selectors.

dart-dom-html.Element.querySelector.selectors should be a string using CSS selector syntax.

// Gets the first descendant with the class 'classname'
var element = element.querySelector('.className');
// Gets the element with id 'id'
var element = element.querySelector('#id');
// Gets the first descendant [ImageElement]
var img = element.querySelector('img');

For details about CSS selector syntax, see the CSS selector specification.

scrollByLines.name: scrollByLines
scrollByLines.comment:
Scrolls the element by a number of lines.

Other resources

  • scrollByLines from WebPlatform.org.

scrollByPages.name: scrollByPages
scrollByPages.comment:
Scrolls the element by a number of pages.

Other resources

  • scrollByPages from WebPlatform.org.

requestFullscreen.name: requestFullscreen
requestFullscreen.comment:
Displays this element fullscreen.

Other resources

  • Using the fullscreen API tutorial from WebPlatform.org.

  • Fullscreen specification from W3C.

requestPointerLock.name: requestPointerLock
requestPointerLock.comment:
Locks the mouse pointer to this element.

Other resources

  • Pointer lock specification from W3C.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-dom-html.Element.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

on.name: on
on.comment: This is an ease-of-use accessor for event streams which should only be used when an explicit accessor is not available.

nodes.name: nodes
nodes.comment: A modifiable list of this node's children.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-dom-html.Element.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-dom-html.Element.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-dom-html.Element.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-dom-html.Element.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-dom-html.Element.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-dom-html.Element.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

insertAllBefore.name: insertAllBefore
insertAllBefore.comment:
Inserts all of the nodes into this node directly before refChild.

See also:

  • dart-dom-html.Element.insertBefore

append.name: append
append.comment:
Adds a node to the end of the child dart-dom-html.Element.nodes list of this node.

If the node already exists in this document, it will be removed from its current parent node, then added to this node.

This method is more efficient than nodes.add, and is the preferred way of appending a child node.

clone.name: clone
clone.comment:
Returns a copy of this node.

If dart-dom-html.Element.clone.deep is true, then all of this node's children and decendents are copied as well. If dart-dom-html.Element.clone.deep is false, then only this node is copied.

Other resources

  • Node.cloneNode from MDN.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment:
Returns true if this node contains the specified node.

Other resources

  • Node.contains from MDN.

hasChildNodes.name: hasChildNodes
hasChildNodes.comment:
Returns true if this node has any children.

Other resources

  • Node.hasChildNodes from MDN.

insertBefore.name: insertBefore
insertBefore.comment:
Inserts all of the nodes into this node directly before refChild.

Other resources

  • Node.insertBefore from MDN.
